But if he apprehende that something more was 'intended by the Poet, 1 avow myself of the same opinion, and will give my reasons for suspecting that he wrote οὐ δρόσοι παγαὶ πατρῷαι, or παγᾶν πατρῷαι, and by this allusion to pert of the nuptial ceremonies of Greeoe, intimated the maiden’s sad reverse of fortune, and the difference of the ap- proaching solemnity from that which she had expected. At wed- dinge a vessel was brought by the λουτροφόρος, filled with water taken from some river or spring deemed sacred in the country or the family, as Callirrhoe at Athens, and Ismenus at Thebes. πηγαὶ πατρῷαι may signify παγαὶ πατρῴας γῆς.
